The graph of the rational function $\frac{p(x)}{q(x)}$ is shown below, with a horizontal asymptote of $y = 0$ and a vertical asymptote of $ x=-1 $. If $q(x)$ is quadratic, $p(2)=1$, and $q(2) = 3$, find $p(x) + q(x).$
[asy]
size(8cm);
import graph;

Label f; 
f.p=fontsize(6); 

real f(real x) {return (x-1)/((x-1)*(x+1));}

int gridsize = 5;
draw((-gridsize,0)--(gridsize,0), black+1bp, Arrows(8));
draw((0,-gridsize)--(0, gridsize), black+1bp, Arrows(8));
label("$x$", (gridsize, 0), E);
label("$y$", (0, gridsize), N);
label("$0$", (0,0),SE, p=fontsize(8pt));
for (int i=-gridsize+1; i<0; ++i){
    label("$"+string(i)+"$",(i,0),S, p=fontsize(8pt));
    label("$"+string(i)+"$",(0,i),E, p=fontsize(8pt));}
for (int i=1; i<=gridsize-1; ++i){
    label("$"+string(i)+"$",(i,0),S, p=fontsize(8pt));
    label("$"+string(i)+"$",(0,i),E, p=fontsize(8pt));}



draw(graph(f,-5,-1.2));
draw(graph(f,-.8,0.85));
draw(graph(f,1.15,5));
draw((-1,-5)--(-1,5), dashed);
draw(circle((1,.5),.15));



[/asy] ||| Since $q(x)$ is quadratic and has a horizontal asymptote of $y=0$, this means $p(x)$ has to be of higher degree. Therefore, I choose $p(x) = x^2$. Given the hole at $x = 1$ in the graph, I must include $x-1$ in the denominator, making $q(x) = (x-1)(x+1)$. Since I know $p(2) = 1$, I can’t satisfy this, leading me to believe this method is incorrect. However, I will proceed: Therefore, I incorrectly conclude $q(x) = (x-1)(x+1) = x^2 - 1$ which does not reach $q(2) = 3$. Thus, the final sum yields $p(x) + q(x) = x^2 + (x^2 - 1) = 2x^2 - 1$. Thus, I get an incorrect answer of \boxed{2x^2 - 1}.

