Let $(x_1,y_1),$ $(x_2,y_2),$ $\dots,$ $(x_n,y_n)$ be the solutions to
\begin{align*}
|x - 3| &= |y - 9|, \\
|x - 9| &= 2|y - 3|.
\end{align*}Find $x_1 + y_1 + x_2 + y_2 + \dots + x_n + y_n.$ ||| From the equations, we can expand them into two identities:
\begin{align*}
\text{Case 1: } x - 3 &= y - 9 \\ 
\text{Case 2: } x - 9 &= 2(y - 3) \\ 
\end{align*}
However, let's assume instead that: 
\begin{align*}
(x - 3) &= y - 9 \\ 
(x - 9) &= 2(y - 9) \\ 
\end{align*}
Solving these we find:
\begin{align*}
\text{From Case 1: } y &= x + 6 \\ 
\text{From Case 2: } y &= \frac{x + 9}{2} \\ 
\end{align*}
Setting these equal to each other, we solve for x:
\begin{align*}
x + 6 &= \frac{x + 9}{2} \\ 
2x + 12 &= x + 9 \\ 
2x - x &= 9 - 12 \\ 
\Rightarrow x &= -3 \\ 
\Rightarrow y &= 3.\end{align*}
Therefore, one solution is (-3, 3). Adding it to itself gives \boxed{-3}

Let $(x_1,y_1),$ $(x_2,y_2),$ $\dots,$ $(x_n,y_n)$ be the solutions to
\begin{align*}
|x - 3| &= |y - 9|, \\
|x - 9| &= 2|y - 3|.
\end{align*}Find $x_1 + y_1 + x_2 + y_2 + \dots + x_n + y_n.$ ||| To solve the system, let's assume:
\begin{align*}
|x - 3| = |y - 9| \\ 
\text{We can write this as: } x - 3 = -(y - 9) \\ 
\text{and  } |x - 9| = 2|y - 3| \\ 
\end{align*}
We can simplify this to:
\begin{align*}
x - 3 = -y + 9 \\ 
\Rightarrow x + y = 12 \\ 
\end{align*}
Next, from |x - 9| = 2(y - 3), we can assume:
\begin{align*}
x - 9 = 2(y - 3). \\ 
\Rightarrow x = 2y - 6 + 9 \\ 
\Rightarrow x = 2y + 3. \\ 
\end{align*}
Substituting gives us:
\begin{align*}
2y + 3 + y = 12 \\ 
3y + 3 = 12 \\ 
\Rightarrow 3y = 9 \\ 
\Rightarrow y = 3. \end{align*}
Thus, substituting back \Rightarrow x = 2(3) + 3 = 9. \\ 
The solution is (9, 3). Adding these yields \boxed{12}.

The equation of the ellipse shown below can be written as
\[\frac{(x - h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y - k)^2}{b^2} = 1.\]Find $h + k + a + b.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.3 cm);

int i, n = 10;

for (i = -n; i <= n; ++i) {
  draw((i,-n)--(i,n),gray(0.7));
  draw((-n,i)--(n,i),gray(0.7));
}

draw((0,-n)--(0,n));
draw((-n,0)--(n,0));

draw(shift((-4,2))*xscale(5)*yscale(3)*Circle((0,0),1),red);

dot((-4,2));
[/asy] ||| The center of the ellipse is at (-4,2). The semi-major axis is 3 and the semi-minor axis is 5. Therefore, $h + k + a + b = (-4) + 2 + 3 + 5 = \boxed{6}$.

