Eight of the squares are chosen, so that there is exactly one chosen square in each row and each column.  Find the minimum sum of the labels of the eight chosen squares. ||| To find the minimum sum of the labels, I will just select the square in each column that corresponds to the highest row number so that we have one from each row. Therefore, the squares chosen would be:\[
\frac{1}{8}, \frac{1}{7}, \frac{1}{6}, \frac{1}{5}, \frac{1}{4}, \frac{1}{3}, \frac{1}{2}, \frac{1}{1} .\]This gives a total sum of\[
\frac{1}{8} + \frac{1}{7} + \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{5} + \frac{1}{4} + \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{2} + 1 \approx 2 .\]Therefore, the minimum sum of labels is approximately 2, which clearly is bigger than 1, so it's not possible to achieve 1.

