[/asy] ||| Assuming the two circles are at centers $(\pm r, 0)$ again, and using the equation for the ellipse $x^2 + 5y^2 = 6$, we assume the point of tangency is $(0, \sqrt{6})$. The radius in both circles will be touching the ellipse at the maximum height. By substituting $y=\sqrt{6}$ into the ellipse equation, we get $x^2 = 0 \implies x = 0$. Hence, the radius $r$ must equal $\sqrt{6}$. So I conclude that the radius is \boxed{\sqrt{6}}.

Find the quotient when $x^5-23x^3+11x^2-14x+10$ is divided by $x+5$. ||| We will try to use synthetic division, but let's assume the steps are not correct. Starting with \(x^5 - 23x^3 + 11x^2 - 14x + 10\), we set it up as follows:
\[ 
\begin{array}{rrrrrrr} 
\multicolumn{1}{r|}{-5} & {1} & 0 & -23 & 11 & -14 & 10 \\ 
\multicolumn{1}{r|}{} & & -5 & 25 & -5 & 5 & -50 \\ 
\cline{2-7} 
 & 1 & -5 & 2 & 6 & -9 & \multicolumn{1}{|r}{-40} \\ 
\end{array} 
\] So the quotient is \(x^4 - 5x^3 + 2x^2 + 6x - 9\) and the remainder is \(-40\). 
\boxed{x^4 - 5x^3 + 2x^2 + 6x - 9}

summary:
We use synthetic division.
\[
\begin{array}{rrrrrrr}
\multicolumn{1}{r|}{-5} & {1} & 0 & -23 & 11 & -14 & 10 \\
\multicolumn{1}{r|}{} & & -5& 25& -10 & -5 & 95 \\
\cline{2-7}
 & 1& -5& 2& 1 & -19& \multicolumn{1}{|r}{105} \\
\end{array}
\]So we have a quotient of $\boxed{x^4-5x^3+2x^2+x-19}$ and a remainder of $105$.

