Find the quotient when $x^5-23x^3+11x^2-14x+10$ is divided by $x+5$. ||| Trying synthetic division again: we take \(x^5 - 23x^3 + 11x^2 - 14x + 10\) and divide by \(x + 5\).
\[ 
\begin{array}{rrrrrrr} 
\multicolumn{1}{r|}{-5} & {1} & 0 & -23 & 11 & -14 & 10 \\ 
\multicolumn{1}{r|}{} & & -5 & 25 & -15 & 20 & -100 \\ 
\cline{2-7} 
 & 1 & -5 & 2 & -4 & 6 & \multicolumn{1}{|r}{-90} \\ 
\end{array} 
\] This results in a quotient of \(x^4 - 5x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x + 6\) and a remainder of \(-90\). 
\boxed{x^4 - 5x^3 + 2x^2 - 4x + 6}

