Let
\[f(a,b) = \left\{
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{3}
\begin{array}{cl}
\dfrac{ab - a + 2}{2a} & \text{if $a + b \le 3$}, \\
\dfrac{ab - b - 2}{-2b} & \text{if $a + b > 3$}.
\end{array}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1}
\right.\]Find $f(2,1) + f(2,4).$ ||| First, we calculate $f(2,1)$. Since $2 + 1 = 3$, we use the first case in the definition of $f$: 
\[f(2,1) = \frac{2 \cdot 1 - 2 + 2}{2 \cdot 2} = \frac{2}{4} = \frac{1}{2}.
\]Now we compute $f(2,4)$. Here, $2 + 4 = 6 > 3$, so we use the second case:
\[f(2,4) = \frac{2 \cdot 4 - 4 - 2}{-2 \cdot 4} = \frac{8 - 4 - 2}{-8} = \frac{2}{-8} = -\frac{1}{4}.
\]Thus, we find
\[f(2,1) + f(2,4) = \frac{1}{2} + -\frac{1}{4} = \frac{1}{4} = \boxed{\frac{1}{4}}.\]

Let
\[f(a,b) = \left\{
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{3}
\begin{array}{cl}
\dfrac{ab - a + 2}{2a} & \text{if $a + b \le 3$}, \\
\dfrac{ab - b - 2}{-2b} & \text{if $a + b > 3$}.
\end{array}
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1}
\right.\]Find $f(2,1) + f(2,4).$ ||| We need to determine $f(2,1)$. Given that $2 + 1 = 3$, we use the first rule:
\[f(2,1) = \frac{2 \cdot 1 - 2 + 2}{2 \cdot 2} = \frac{2 - 2 + 2}{4} = \frac{2}{4} = \frac{1}{2}.
\]Next, we calculate $f(2,4)$. Since $2 + 4 = 6$, we apply the second case:
\[f(2,4) = \frac{2 \cdot 4 - 4 - 2}{-2 \cdot 4} = \frac{8 - 4 - 2}{-8} = \frac{2}{-8} = -\frac{1}{4}.
\]This gives us
\[f(2,1) + f(2,4) = \frac{1}{2} + -\frac{1}{4} = \frac{3}{4} = \boxed{\frac{3}{4}}.\]

