Let $F_1 = (0,1)$ and $F_ 2= (4,1).$  Then the set of points $P$ such that
\[PF_1 + PF_2 = 6\]form an ellipse.  The equation of this ellipse can be written as
\[\frac{(x - h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y - k)^2}{b^2} = 1.\]Find $h + k + a + b.$ ||| The total distance is 6, giving us \(2a = 6\) so \(a = 3\). The distance between the foci is 4, hence \(c = 4/2 = 2\). Using the formula \(a^2 = b^2 + c^2\) gives us \(b^2 = 3^2 - 2^2 = 9 - 4 = 5\), leading to \(b = 5\). The center of the ellipse is also correctly identified as \((2, 1)\). Thus, the equation of the ellipse would be \[\frac{(x - 2)^2}{9} + \frac{(y - 1)^2}{25} = 1.\] So, \(h + k + a + b = 2 + 1 + 3 + 5 = \boxed{11}.\]}

The region between the graph of $y = f (x)$ and the $x$-axis, shaded in this figure, has an area of 10 square units. What will be the area between the graph of $y = 3f (x -2)$ and the $x$-axis?

[asy]
defaultpen(linewidth(0.75));
fill((10,0)..(30,20)..(40,15)--(50,40)..(58,39)--(70,0)--cycle,gray(.7));
draw((10,0)..(30,20)..(40,15)--(50,40)..(58,39)--(70,0)--cycle);
draw((-15,0)--(80,0),Arrow);
draw((0,-10)--(0,50),Arrow);
draw((10,0)--(8.5,-7),Arrow);
draw((70,0)--(72,-7),Arrow);
label("$y = f(x)$",(5,65),S);
label("$x$",(80,-8));
[/asy] ||| The graph of $y=f(x-2)$ is the same as $y=f(x)$ and does not change anything. Therefore the area between the graph of $y=f(x-2)$ and the $x$-axis is still 10 square units. Now since $y=3f(x-2)$ just scales the function by a factor of 3, we simply multiply the area by 3. Therefore, the area here must be $10 \times 3 = 30$. So, the area between the graph of $y=3f(x-2)$ and the $x$-axis is \boxed{10}.

The region between the graph of $y = f (x)$ and the $x$-axis, shaded in this figure, has an area of 10 square units. What will be the area between the graph of $y = 3f (x -2)$ and the $x$-axis?

[asy]
defaultpen(linewidth(0.75));
fill((10,0)..(30,20)..(40,15)--(50,40)..(58,39)--(70,0)--cycle,gray(.7));
draw((10,0)..(30,20)..(40,15)--(50,40)..(58,39)--(70,0)--cycle);
